{{Infobox ethnic group | group = Romani people in Algeria | population = >2,500 | popplace = | langs = ? [[Romani language|Romani]], [[French language|French]] | rels = [[Islam]]<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=54gyRnhIugkC&pg=PA236&dq=algeria+nawar+gypsies&hl=en&sa=X&ei=G4w0VK3ZGNioyATqq4KwAg&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=algeria%20nawar%20gypsies&f=false Peoples on the Move: Introducing the Nomads of the World. By David J. Phillips]</ref> | related = [[Dom people]], [[Nawar people]], [[Kawliya]] }}
'''Romani people in Algeria''' are reported to include at least two groups: the Afrikaya, and the [[Xoraxane]]. The Afrikaya are possibly of [[Manouche]] origins, and speak [[French language|French]]. The Xoraxane are Muslim and their original language is [[Romani language|Romani]]. Roma in general ultimately come from [[South Asia]], particularly from [[North India|Northern]] [[India]], having reached the Mediterranean region in [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] times.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=54gyRnhIugkC&pg=PA236&dq=algeria+nawar+gypsies&hl=en&sa=X&ei=G4w0VK3ZGNioyATqq4KwAg&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=algeria%20nawar%20gypsies&f=false Peoples on the Move: Introducing the Nomads of the World. By David J. Phillips]</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Berland |first=Joseph C. |date=2004 |title=Customary Strangers: New Perspectives on Peripatetic Peoples in the Middle East, Africa, and Asia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8CAv53wlHfoC&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71&dq=syria+nawar+gypsies&source=bl&ots=v0pNj8AaZn&sig=k5b8IZoSObUqPHqO2dKY_qWDOHY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-rVvUojQKPT54APk24DACA&ved=0CE8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=Westport, Connecticut |publisher=Praeger Publishers |isbn=0-89789-771-4 |accessdate=2013-10-28 }}</ref>
