{{Infobox ethnic group | group = Romani people in Egypt | population = 2,300,000<ref>[http://joshuaproject.net/people_groups/11597/EG Gypsy, Domari in Egypt]</ref> | popplace = | langs = [[Domari language|Domari]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Berber languages|Berber]] | rels = [[Islam]], [[Romani mythology|Romani religion]] | related = [[Dom people]], [[Nawar people]], [[Kawliya]] }}
'''Romani people in Egypt''' speak the [[Domari language]]. They immigrated to the territory of the present day Egypt from [[South Asia]], particularly from [[India]], in [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] times. [[Romani people|Romani]] ([[Dom people|Dom]] or [[Nawar people|Nawar]]) people self-segregated themselves for centuries from the dominant culture of Egypt, who view Romani as dishonorable though clever. Historically, Gypsies in Egypt have provided musical entertainment at weddings and other celebrations. The Romani people or Gypsies in Egypt include subgroups like Nawar, Halebi and Ghagar.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=54gyRnhIugkC&pg=PA236&dq=egypt+nawar+gypsies&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAGoVChMI5OfS5MS7xwIVSH6SCh269AMm#v=onepage&q=egypt%20nawar%20gypsies&f=false Peoples on the Move: Introducing the Nomads of the World. By David J. Phillips]</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Berland |first=Joseph C. |date=2004 |title=Customary Strangers: New Perspectives on Peripatetic Peoples in the Middle East, Africa, and Asia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8CAv53wlHfoC&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71&dq=syria+nawar+gypsies&source=bl&ots=v0pNj8AaZn&sig=k5b8IZoSObUqPHqO2dKY_qWDOHY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-rVvUojQKPT54APk24DACA&ved=0CE8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=Westport, Connecticut |publisher=Praeger Publishers |isbn=0-89789-771-4 |accessdate=2013-10-28 }}</ref>
