{{Infobox language | name = Rutul | nativename = мыхӀабишды чӀел ''myxʼabišdy č̣el'' | pronunciation = [mɨxabiʃdɨ t͡ʃʼɛl] | states = [[Russia]], [[Azerbaijan]] | region = Southern [[Dagestan]], Russian–Azerbaijani border | ethnicity = [[Rutul people|Rutul]] | speakers = 36,400 | date = 2010 census | ref = <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/rut|title=Rutul|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-07-31|language=en}}</ref> | familycolor = Caucasian | fam1 = [[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian]] | fam2 = [[Lezgic languages|Lezgic]] | fam3 = [[Samur languages|Samur]] | fam4 = [[Western Samur languages|Western Samur]] | script = [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] | nation = {{flag|Dagestan}} | map = Caucasus-ethnic roetoelen.png | mapcaption = Rutul in the Caucasus | iso3 = rut | glotto = rutu1240 | glottorefname = Rutul }}
'''Rutul''' is a language spoken by the [[Rutul people|Rutuls]], an ethnic group living in [[Dagestan]] ([[Russia]]) and some parts of [[Azerbaijan]]. It is spoken by 30,000 people in Dagestan (2010 census)<ref>[http://www.gks.ru/free_doc/new_site/population/demo/per-itog/tab6.xls Информационные материалы об окончательных итогах Всероссийской переписи населения 2010 года]</ref> and 17,000 (no date) in Azerbaijan.<ref name=e17>{{e17|rut}}</ref> The word ''Rutul'' derives from the name of a Dagestani village where speakers of this language make up the majority.<ref name="rutetheo">{{ru icon}} [http://etheo.h10.ru/rutu01.htm ETHEO: Rutul Language]</ref>{{broken citation|date=January 2010}}
Rutul is [[endangered language|endangered]] in Russia<ref>[http://www.helsinki.fi/~tasalmin/chris.html Published in: Encyclopedia of the world’s endangered languages. Edited by Christopher Moseley. London & New York: Routledge, 2007. 211–280.]</ref> and classified as "definitely endangered" by [[UNESCO]]'s [[Atlas of the World's Languages in Danger]].<ref>[http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/index.php?pg=00206 UNESCO Interactive Atlas of the World’s Languages in Danger]</ref> <!--UNESCO Endangered Language Criteria: 1. Vulnerable, 2. Definitely Endangered, 3. Severely Endangered, 4. Critically Endangered, 5. Extinct-->
==Classification== Rutul belongs to the [[Lezgic languages|Lezgic group]] of the [[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian]] language family. The [[Rutul people|Rutuls]] call their language '''myxʼabišdy čʼel'''.
==History== Rutul was not a written language until the writing system for it (based on [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]]) was developed in 1990. A Latin alphabet was developed in 2013 based on the Shin-Shorsu dialect.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.sil.org/system/files/reapdata/71/16/90/71169050965608079497039264944293532638/SILForum2015_002.pdf |title= Important Factors in the Development of an Orthography: Shin-Shorsu Rutul—a Case Study |last=Clarkson |first=Jonathan |last2=Iurkova |first2=Elena |series=SIL Forum for Language Fieldwork 2015-002 |publisher=SIL International |date= December 2015 |archive-url= http://www.sil.org/resources/archives/63843 |archivedate=2015 |access-date= 2016-06-22}}</ref> Speakers are often bilingual or multilingual, having a good command of the [[Azeri language|Azeri]], [[Lezgian language|Lezgian]] and/or [[Russian language|Russian]] languages. There are 8 dialects and 2 subdialects of Rutul. The literary version of the language remains in the process of development. In the Rutul-populated regions of southern Russia, Rutul is taught in primary schools (grades 1 to 4).<ref name="rutetheo"/>{{broken citation|date=January 2010}}
==Related languages== Among the languages of the Lezgic group, [[Tsakhur language|Tsakhur]] appears to be the closest relative of Rutul.<ref name="tsketheo">{{ru icon}} [http://etheo.h10.ru/tsax01.htm The Tsakhur language]. The ''ETHEO'' Project. Last updated 11 October 2005. Retrieved 26 December 2006</ref>{{broken citation|date=January 2010}} Other than these two, there are seven more languages in the Lezgic group, namely: [[Lezgian language|Lezgian]], [[Tabasaran language|Tabasaran]], [[Aghul language|Aghul]], [[Budukh language|Budukh]], [[Kryts language|Kryts]], [[Udi language|Udi]] and [[Archi language|Archi]].
[[File:Rutul alphabet.jpg|350x350px|thumbnail|right|Rutul alphabet]]
